    c?
        The loop starts to turn but stops when the loop is vertical because when the loop is flat, Flemming's Left Hand Rule suggests that the left hand side of the loop experiences a downwards force, whereas the right hand side of the loop experiences an upwards force. This is because current is flowing in opposite directions on each side of the loop. This causes the loop to turn because the forces experienced are imbalanced and perpendicular to the plane of the coil.

        However, when the loop is vertical, although the same upwards and downwards forces are experienced, these forces are in-line with the plane of the coil. Thus, the coil only experiences a stretching force vertically, but does not experience any moment.
6.
    a.
        Place the rectangular transparent block in a central spot on the paper, and trace around it using the pencil to denote its position and orientation. This marking should be done in a fashion which allows the drawing of lines normal to the surface of the block later. Then, using the ray box, shine a ray of light into the rectangular transparent block. Mark the point at which the ray of light enters the rectangular transparent block, the point at which the ray of light leaves the rectangular transparent block, and the point at which the ray of light originated (i.e. the position of the ray box). Repeat this process several times, positioning the ray box in a different position each time, making sure to keep track of which markings belong to which repetition.

        After at least ten repetitions, for each group of markings, using the ruler, draw a line between where the light entered the rectangular box and the position of the ray box (hereinafter referred to as the incident line), and a line between where the light entered the rectangular box and where the light exited the box (hereinafter referred to as the refracted line). Also draw a normal (using the protractor if nececssary) at the point where the light entered the box. Then, measure the angle between the incident line and the normal (meaning the acute angle completely outside where the rectangular box was) (hereinafter referred to as i_{x} where x refers to the repetition-number this data-set is for); and measure the angle between the normal and the refracted line (meaning the acute angle completely inside where the rectangular box was) (hereinafter referred to as r_{x}). Define n_{x} = sin(i_{x})/sin(r_{x}).

        Compute n_{x} for each group of points using the above method. Remove any outliers via the use of the test k > 1.5 * IQR + median or k < median - 1.5 * IQR means k is an outlier, and then calculate the mean value of n. THis is the refractive index of the material.
